cs.GT, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.DM, cs.IT

Reasoning: 
1. cs.GT (Game Theory): The paper is primarily focused on learning sparse graphical games and analyzing the sample complexity of recovering the set of pure-strategy Nash equilibria. This falls under the domain of game theory, making cs.GT the most likely sub-category.
2. cs.LG (Machine Learning): The paper uses maximum likelihood estimation to recover the PSNE and analyzes the sample complexity of learning, which falls under the domain of machine learning.
3. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The paper deals with learning and analyzing games, which is a sub-domain of artificial intelligence.
4. cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics): The paper uses VC dimension arguments to analyze the sample complexity, which falls under the domain of discrete mathematics.
5. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper also uses information-theoretic arguments to analyze the sample complexity, which falls under the domain of information theory.
